ce:section.ce:para:
The Ag@Cl-CQDs hybrid was synthesized at room temperature through a photoelectron-assisted in-situ chemical reduction of AgNO3 by using Cl-CQDs, which were having an excellent photoelectron transfer ability under the irradiation of visible light, as reducing agents (Fig. 1
                        ). Firstly, Cl-CQDs were prepared by a one-step microwave synthesis with using sucralose as a precursor, which avoids the requirement of strong acids such as hydrochloric acid (HCl) and thionyl chloride (SOCl2) for Cl doping [37,38,42–44]. Low-magnification TEM image revealed the average size of 6.4 ± 1.7 nm for as-prepared Cl-CQDs (Figs. S1(a and b)). FTIR spectrum of Cl-CQDs showed two pronounced bands at 3370 and 1021 cm−1 corresponded to O–H and C–O stretching vibrations, respectively (Fig. S2) [37,45]. Further, vibrational transitions of C–H, C=O of COOH, C=C, and C–OH were also detected at 2940, 1707, 1631, and 1360 cm−1, respectively (Fig. S2) [37,45,46]. Therefore, Cl-CQDs were predominantly terminated with oxygenic functional groups (assumed in the proposed Cl-CQD structure (Fig. 1d)), which provide a good colloidal stability to Cl-CQDs besides enabling the strong interaction with Ag+ ions during the growth of Ag nanoparticles. Further, Cl-CQDs exhibited two absorption peaks at 234 and 284 nm corresponded to π-π* transitions of the graphitic carbon core and n-π* transitions of the carbonyl (C=O) groups, respectively (Fig. 2
                        a) [47]. Especially, the tailing of 284 nm absorption peak towards NIR region provided Cl-CQDs with exceptional visible light absorption ability, which was considered favorable for the successful conversion of AgNO3 to Ag nanoparticles under visible light irradiation. In addition, the significantly quenched photoluminescence of Cl-CQDs in the presence of known electron acceptors such as 2,4-dinitrotoluene (DNT) confirmed the excellent electron transfer capabilities of photoexcited Cl-CQDs (Fig. 2b) [48,49].
